I

IAction - Interface in de.stock.action
Interface for actions

The action system knows two types of actions which start and stop without the players influence (they run a number of rounds)

- MainEvent can start on his own or by another event.

- SubEvent can be started by another event only.

and one extraordinary

- LevelPack gets chosen by player at startup and has goals to complete to get to next level.
  These level packs are seperated into different level stages and if one is finished the next (more difficult) level stage gets played
  (See LevelPack for further information)

Action developers must instantiate MainEvent, SubEvent or LevelPack
They must not instantiate Action
IEnvironment - Interface in de.stock.environment
Interface for environments

The environment system is seperated into a three element hierarchy

At the very top of the hierarchy is the Location
in the middle is the Area
and at the very bottom is the Group
(Read class headers of those for further information)

A environment can link to another environment if it is a part or member of it but it must be of the same type or one layer below in the hierarchy
(See IEnvironment.linkEnvironment(IEnvironment))

Environment developers must instantiate Area, Group or Location
They must not instantiate Environment
ILevel - Interface in de.stock.level
A level, which is part of a LevelPack, consists of several parts:

- The level stage
  The player starts at the first level stage and if this level stage is passed he gets in the next stage if available.
  He chooses one level pack at the beginning of a level stage.
  If a level is of type normal or award level is indicated through the level stage, see Settings_Level

- The successor
  The next level(s) in a level pack
  A level pack doesn't need to follow a linear order, it can has branches, too.
  If the method getSuccessor() returns null the level pack is over

- The events
  A level may have specific events, which are removed (but not stopped if running) from event observer if a level is passed and added if it gets started

- The tradeables
  A level may have specific tradeables, which are removed from tradeable handler if a level is passed and added if it gets started

- The goal
  The goal to reach to get in the next level

- The prize
  The prize the player gets if he passes the level (if available)

- The award
  The award the player gets if he passes the level (if available)

A LevelPack development guide can be found at the LevelPackLoader

ILevelPack - Interface in de.stock.level
The level system knows two types of level packs:

- The normal level packs which are grouped in level stages
  Only one of these can run at the same time!
  (Level stage 1 and above)

- The award level packs
  Multiple of these can run at the same time!
  (Level stage 0)

A level pack - a packet of several levels - which has a name and a description.

It may has tradeables which are available and events which can occur over the whole playtime of the level pack.
(Every level in a level pack may have specific tradeables or events, too!)

The player can choose from these packs at the beginning of the game and if a level stage is passed, too.

An example is the (not so serious) level pack "Lemonade" with the following levels:

ITradable - Interface in de.stock.tradeable
Interface for tradeables

Tradables, which are stored in the TradableHandler, consist of several parts:

- The value
  Every tradeable has a value at what cost the player can buy one
  The value gets influenced by events respectively environments.
  If a tradeable wasn't influenced by an event the TradableHandler updates the value manually
  using a random value in between the influencable bottom bound and the influencable top bound of the tradeable every round.

- The shares
  Every tradeable has a number of minimum and maximum available shares.
  The number of shares is initialized with ITradable.initializeShares()
  This number varies if the player buys or sells a tradeable.
  (It should change randomly without the players influence, too)

- The environment
  Every tradeable is part of one or more environments.
  Example: Wheat is part of the Group cereal

A tradeable is from type Stock, Commodity, Forex or Derivate and a developer must instantiate from these classes.
He must not instantiate the Tradable class!

Its the key element to earn money in this game.
